@NODE CzechIntro CzechPatch.guide/Introduction

@{" << Home  " Link Main}    @{b}Introduction to CzechPatch@{ub}    @{" Contents >> " Link CzechContn}

As I downloaded czech locale support for my Amiga, I've noticed that the
supplied fonts for ISO Latin II characters simply overwrite the old ones.
Since I'm not a czech user I also need the ISO Latin I fonts.
Now I looked for a method to use them both in parallel. Most programs
allow you to select a font in their settings. But if you swap the
character standard you have to change over hundred of program settings
to reflect the new standard. And this is the point where this program
jumps in:
It allows you to maintenance different ISO standards on your system
by simply giving the ISO Latin II fonts a different name. The fonts
I got all have -CZ.font or -WinEE.font (i.e. topaz.font becomes
topaz-CZ.font or topaz-WinEE.font respectively). So I got the idea
to write a patch program that patches both graphics.library's OpenFont()
as well as diskfont.library's OpenDiskFont() which tries, when enabled,
to open fonts with a -CZ or -WinEE first and if that fails (the user
does not have an ISO Latin II version of this font), it opens the normal
font name passed to the library function. This means that you have to
rename all your ISO Latin II fonts in a way that there's a -CZ or -WinEE
before the .font extension.

         @{b}CzechPatch will solve this problem on the fly!@{ub}

Please note that you have to call FixFonts (found in SYS:System) after
you've renamed any fonts.

@{i}@{b}Advantages:@{ui}@{ub}

@{b}*@{ub}  Very small in size (3200 bytes, 100% Assembler,
source code included)

@{b}*@{ub}  The appended name is changeable for all who don't have ISO II fonts
ending with -CZ.font (%s-CZ%s). This means if you call e.g. OpenFont()
with topaz.font, it will try to open first topaz-CZ.font and if this
fails it will fallback to original topaz.font.

@{b}*@{ub}  Works on ANY Amiga

@{b}*@{ub}  Locale support for OS2.1+

@{b}*@{ub}  Dedicated to Zuzana Burkertová. I love you!


