@NODE CzechInsta CzechPatch.guide/Installing

@{" << Home  " Link Main}    @{b}Installation instructions@{ub}    @{" Usage >> " Link CzechUsage}

@{b}(User install)@{ub}

Simply copy the file Utils/CzechPatch somewhere to your Path (e.g. C:)
@{b}Copy Utils/CzechPatch TO C: CLONE@{ub}

If you want to have locale support, then copy catalogs
to LOCALE:catalogs
@{b}Copy catalogs TO LOCALE:catalogs ALL CLONE

@{b}(Installing upgrades)@{ub}

To install an upgraded version of CzechPatch, overwrite the
existing CzechPatch program after you turned the old version off
(type @{b}CzechPatch OFF@{ub} for this) with the new one, and turn the
new version on with: @{b}CzechPatch ON@{ub}.
Before you turn on the new version you should copy the new catalogs
and type @{b}Avail FLUSH@{ub} in order to remove the old ones from memory.


@{" << Home  " Link Main}  Back to the table of contents.

@ENDNODE


@NODE CzechUsage CzechPatch.guide/Usage

@{" << Home  " Link Main}    @{b}Usage of CzechPatch@{ub}    @{" History >> " Link CzechHisto}


Installing the patch can be simply done with typing:
@{b}CzechPatch@{ub}

which should inform you about that it was installed. If it was already
installed it will remove from system.

However you can also pass extra arguments, e.g.:
@{b}CzechPatch ON@{ub}

which forces CzechPatch to be turned on (when it's already on it will do
nothing).

Of course, the opposite:
@{b}CzechPatch OFF@{ub}

exists, it forces CzechPatch to be turned off. This might not be possible
if the OpenFont() and/or OpenDiskFont() library vectors were changed
after installing. In this case undo these changes.

You also can customize the name of the ISO Latin II fonts:
@{b}CzechPatch -f I_love_%s_Burkertová%s

When a program opens e.g. @{b}Zuzka.font@{ub}, it will try now first to open
@{b}I_love_Zuzka_Burkertová.font@{ub}.
Sounds complicated? 
It's really simple. The format string consists of two %s which will be
replaced by the file name and the file extension (usually .font). The
first %s is always replaced with the file name of the font and the
second %s is always replaced with the name of the font.
If you ommit this, the default @{b}%s-CZ%s@{ub} will be used in which case the
example above will try to open: @{b}Zuzka-CZ.font@{ub}.
If your ISO Latin II characters end with -WinEE.font, type:
@{b}CzechPatch -f %s-WinEE%s@{ub}

Of course, you can combine -f and the ON/OFF switches:
@{b}CzechPatch ON -f %s-WinEE%s@{ub}

Another useful thing is:
@{b}CzechPatch ON -f topaz.font@{ub}

This will open always topaz.font, regardless what font a program tries to
open. So you can use this tool also for replacing the ugly looking game
font ;-)

@{b}CzechPatch ?@{ub} gives small usage help.


